[4]It appears in may, at the foot of the rock roses with sage leaves, where its bright colors (yellow to red), betray in the middle of a carpet of their fallen leaves.
[5]Reaching up to 6 cm, it has little more than a centimeter around its flower end.It was known under the name of the juice of hypocistis, a multiple components theriac the pharmacopoeia western sea in the post-Maistral, in Yannick Romieux, Of the hune to the mortar, Editions ACL, Nantes, 1986.
